I had to respond that there is no clear macrometer, when the phrases themselves are clearly broken into lopsided groups of 2 and 3 dotted quarters. Those lopsided groups then combine to produce 9- and 14-dotted-quarter bars that are totally regular. In other words, periodicity is extremely strong, but the meter is not square enough to fit into the questions asked.

transcr_text: This entire transcription misrepresents my hearing of the rhythm of the song. I could see how someone would hear it as duple division, but to me this is a clear, and typically European lilt (especially the way she performs it). The issue it would seem is that the lilt is so slight that it sounds almost straight, but it's not straight enough to be straight (like a Dixie swing). There is a swung, or lilting character here that simply does not jibe at all with a straight hearing (again, in my opinion, of course). This is why I have my basic tapping value as a dotted quarter (this dotted quarter shows as a quarter in the transcription).

transcr_text: Sorry to put "terrible," but to my ears this is not what I heard. First, I hear everything in triple division (not just the notated triplets). While these triplets are often uneven, they do not sound like dotted-eighth sixteenth rhythms to me. Second, his initial intoning is certainly on B, but it is quite a high B. Because of this, when he sinks slightly to begin the first phrase, the D# is really just a high D, likewise with the C# (C). For me, this sounds Phrygian with a clear semitone above the tonic B and a flat mediant.

comment_song: 99:99 The solo man is always four beats long, but the group singing varies from 3 beats to 20 or so. No discernible pattern in how long the group singing is, thus no consistent meter. Probably improvised - the group knows to stop singing if the solo guy goes into the 4-beat phrase.

99:99 Although I noted that there is a "clear macrometer throughout," that macrometer being essentially 6/8, the hypermeter or phrase groupings vary widely. In most of these songs it has been possible to enter something like 6/8 AND 12/8, but here that 12/8 level is not possible since there is so much variation between two-measure ideas.

00:25 When other voices enter to sing a kind of response to the song leader, they begin on Unison Fifths. However, as the song progresses, it introduces clear triadic harmony! However, this triadic harmony shifts between major and minor throughout the track. Really fascinating - I wonder if it has to do with a reaction to the text (or perhaps it was unintentional).

99:99 The song appears to move through different modules, with little concern for the key being consistent b/w modules. W/i modules, the key is more fixed, and tends to be minor pentatonic. The first half makes it seem like this will be repetitive song: the first system is repeated several times, then the material that begins in system 5 is repeated several times. Following this, though, the song appears to go through a series of different and new modules.

99:99 Tough to address pitch/tonal content in this one in accordance with these questions because of successive modulation. Also, some of the pitches "float" a fair amount above or below their notated levels. For the tonal centers, I chose one from the beginning and one from the end. But there are several different centers throughout the song.

Later, groups of 11 or 12 are prominent, before clear groups of 4 emerge with the very rapid tempo quarters near the end. I answered "7" and "4" for the macrometer since these were the two strongest emergent meters I heard. Also, there is one membrano-idio-phone instrument.
